# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-reverb-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] An **all-pass filter** is a signal processing filter that passes all frequencies equally in gain, but changes the phase relationship among various frequencies.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] Most types of filter reduce the amplitude (i.e. the magnitude) of the signal applied to it for some values of frequency, whereas the all-pass filter allows all frequencies through without changes in level.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] A common application in electronic music production is in the design of an effects unit known as a "phaser", where a number of all-pass filters are connected in sequence and the output mixed with the raw signal.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] It does this by varying its phase shift as a function of frequency.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] Generally, the filter is described by the frequency at which the phase shift crosses 90° (i.e., when the input and output signals go into quadrature – when there is a quarter wavelength of delay between them).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] They are generally used to compensate for other undesired phase shifts that arise in the system, or for mixing with an unshifted version of the original to implement a notch comb filter.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] They may also be used to convert a mixed phase filter into a minimum phase filter with an equivalent magnitude response or an unstable filter into a stable filter with an equivalent magnitude response.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] which has one pole at -1/RC and one zero at 1/RC (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the imaginary axis of the complex plane).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The filter has unity-gain magnitude for all ω.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase shift is 90°).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a low-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the low-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] where T is the delay (in seconds) and $s\in \mathbb {C}$ is complex frequency.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] where the last step was achieved via a first-order Taylor series expansion of the numerator and denominator.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] By setting $RC=T/2$ we recover $H(s)$ from above.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The operational amplifier circuit shown in the adjacent figure implements a single-pole active all-pass filter that features a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input of the opamp.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The filter introduces a different delay at each frequency and reaches input-to-output *quadrature* at ω=1/RC (i.e., phase lead is 90°).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] This implementation uses a high-pass filter at the non-inverting input to generate the phase shift and negative feedback.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] In fact, the phase shift of the all-pass filter is double the phase shift of the high-pass filter at its non-inverting input.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The resistor can be replaced with a FET in its *ohmic mode* to implement a voltage-controlled phase shifter; the voltage on the gate adjusts the phase shift.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] In electronic music, a phaser typically consists of two, four or six of these phase-shifting sections connected in tandem and summed with the original.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] A low-frequency oscillator (LFO) ramps the control voltage to produce the characteristic swooshing sound.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The benefit to implementing all-pass filters with active components like operational amplifiers is that they do not require inductors, which are bulky and costly in integrated circuit designs.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] In other applications where inductors are readily available, all-pass filters can be implemented entirely without active components.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] There are a number of circuit topologies that can be used for this.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The following are the most commonly used circuits.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The **lattice phase equaliser**, or **filter**, is a filter composed of lattice, or X-sections.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] With single element branches it can produce a phase shift up to 180°, and with resonant branches it can produce phase shifts up to 360°.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The filter is an example of a constant-resistance network (i.e., its image impedance is constant over all frequencies).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The phase equaliser based on T topology is the unbalanced equivalent of the lattice filter and has the same phase response.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] While the circuit diagram may look like a low pass filter it is different in that the two inductor branches are mutually coupled.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] This results in transformer action between the two inductors and an all-pass response even at high frequency.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The bridged T topology is used for delay equalisation, particularly the differential delay between two landlines being used for stereophonic sound broadcasts.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] This application requires that the filter has a linear phase response with frequency (i.e., constant group delay) over a wide bandwidth and is the reason for choosing this topology.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] which has a zero at $1/{\overline {z_{0}}}$ , where ${\overline {z}}$ denotes the complex conjugate.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The pole and zero sit at the same angle but have reciprocal magnitudes (i.e., they are *reflections* of each other across the boundary of the complex unit circle).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] The placement of this pole-zero pair for a given $z_{0}$ can be rotated in the complex plane by any angle and retain its all-pass magnitude characteristic.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] Complex pole-zero pairs in all-pass filters help control the frequency where phase shifts occur.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] where $y[k]$ is the output and $x[k]$ is the input at discrete time step k .
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] Filters such as the above can be cascaded with unstable or mixed-phase filters to create a stable or minimum-phase filter without changing the magnitude response of the system.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/all-pass-filter] For example, by proper choice of $z_{0}$ , a pole of an unstable system that is outside of the unit circle can be canceled and reflected inside the unit circle.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] In signal processing, a **comb filter** is a filter implemented by adding a delayed version of a signal to itself, causing constructive and destructive interference.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The frequency response of a comb filter consists of a series of regularly spaced notches in between regularly spaced *peaks* (sometimes called *teeth*), giving the appearance of a comb.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Comb filters exist in two forms, *feedforward* and *feedback*, which refer to the direction in which signals are delayed before they are added to the input.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Comb filters may be implemented in discrete time or continuous time forms, which are very similar.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] In acoustics, comb filtering can arise as an unwanted artifact.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] For instance, two loudspeakers playing the same signal at different distances from the listener create a comb filtering effect on the audio.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] In any enclosed space, listeners hear a mixture of direct sound and reflected sound.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The reflected sound takes a longer, delayed path compared to the direct sound, and a comb filter is created where the two mix at the listener.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Similarly, comb filtering may result from mono mixing of multiple mics, hence the 3:1 rule of thumb that neighboring mics should be separated at least three times the distance from its source to the mic.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] where K is the delay length (measured in samples), and *α* is a scaling factor applied to the delayed signal.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The frequency response of a discrete-time system expressed in the *z*-domain is obtained by substitution $z=e^{j\omega },$ where j is the imaginary unit and $\omega$ is angular frequency.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Often of interest is the *magnitude* response, which ignores phase.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The $(1+\alpha ^{2})$ term is constant, whereas the $2\alpha \cos(\omega K)$ term varies periodically.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Hence, the magnitude response of the comb filter is periodic.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The feedforward comb filter is one of the simplest finite impulse response filters.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Its response is simply the initial impulse with a second impulse after the delay.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] the numerator is equal to zero whenever *zK* = −*α*.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] This has *K* solutions, equally spaced around a circle in the complex plane; these are the zeros of the transfer function.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The denominator is zero at *zK* = 0, giving *K* poles at *z* = 0.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] This leads to a pole–zero plot like the ones shown.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Again, the response is periodic, as the graphs demonstrate.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The feedback comb filter is a simple type of infinite impulse response filter.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] If stable, the response simply consists of a repeating series of impulses decreasing in amplitude over time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] This time, the numerator is zero at *zK* = 0, giving *K* zeros at *z* = 0.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The denominator is equal to zero whenever *zK* = *α*.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] This has *K* solutions, equally spaced around a circle in the complex plane; these are the poles of the transfer function.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] This leads to a pole–zero plot like the ones shown below.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Comb filters may also be implemented in continuous time, which can be expressed in the Laplace domain as a function of the complex frequency domain parameter $s=\sigma +j\omega$ analogous to the z domain.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Analog circuits use some form of analog delay line for the delay element.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] Continuous-time implementations share all the properties of the respective discrete-time implementations.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] where *τ* is the delay (measured in seconds).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The feedforward form consists of an infinite number of zeros spaced along the jω axis (which corresponds to the Fourier domain).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/comb-filter] The feedback form consists of an infinite number of poles spaced along the jω axis.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay effects range from a subtle echo effect to a pronounced blending of previous sounds with new sounds.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay effects can be created using tape loops, an approach developed in the 1940s and 1950s and used by artists including Elvis Presley and Buddy Holly.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Analog effects units were introduced in the 1970s; digital effects pedals in 1984; and audio plug-in software in the 2000s.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The first delay effects were achieved using tape loops improvised on reel-to-reel audio tape recording systems.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] By shortening or lengthening the loop of tape and adjusting the read-and-write heads, the nature of the delayed echo could be controlled.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] American producer Sam Phillips created a slapback echo effect with two Ampex 350 tape recorders in 1954.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The effect was used by artists including Elvis Presley (such as on his track "Blue Moon of Kentucky") and Buddy Holly, and became one of Phillips' signatures.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Guitarist and instrument designer Les Paul was an early pioneer in delay devices.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Tape echoes became commercially available in the 1950s.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Tape echo machines contain loops of tape that pass over a record head and then a playback head.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] An **echo machine** is the early name for a sound processing device used with electronic instruments to repeat the sound and produce a simulated echo.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The time between echo repeats was adjusted by varying head position or tape speed.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The length or intensity of the echo effect was adjusted by changing the amount of echo signal fed back into the signal recorded to tape.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] A landmark device was the EchoSonic made by American Ray Butts.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] It is a portable guitar amplifier with a built-in tape echo, which became used widely in country music (Chet Atkins) and especially in rock and roll (Scotty Moore).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Dedicated machines for creating tape loops were introduced.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] One example is the Echoplex, which uses a tape loop.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The length of delay is adjusted by changing the distance between the tape record and playback heads.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Another is the Ace Tone EC-1 Echo Chamber.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] With the Roland RE-201, introduced in 1973, Japanese engineer Ikutaro Kakehashi refined the tape delay to make it more reliable and robust, with reduced tape wear and noise, wow, and flutter, additional controls, and additional tape heads.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Different effects could be created by enabling different combinations of playback heads.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] By adjusting the controls and tape speed, musicians could create pitch-shifting and oscillated effects.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The RE-201 was used by acts including Brian Setzer, Bob Marley, Portishead, and Radiohead.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In the 1970s, Jamaican dub reggae producers used delay effects extensively; Lee "Scratch" Perry created "lo-fi sci-fi" effects by using delay and reverb on a mixing console test tone and dub techno producers such as Basic Channel introduced delay to electronic music.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Digital delay effects were developed with the arrival of digital recording.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Before the invention of audio delay technology, music employing an echo had to be recorded in a naturally reverberant space, often an inconvenience for musicians and engineers.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The demand for an easy-to-use real-time echo effect led to the production of systems offering an all-in-one effects unit that could be adjusted to produce echoes of any interval or amplitude.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The presence of multiple *taps* (playback heads) made it possible to have delays at varying rhythmic intervals; this allowed musicians an additional means of expression over natural periodic echoes.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Early experiments such as send tape echo echo delay (STEED) at Abbey Road Studios used standard and modified reel-to-reel tape recorders to produce delay.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay processors based on analog tape recording use magnetic tape as their recording and playback medium.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Electric motors guide a tape loop through a device with a variety of mechanisms allowing modification of the effect's parameters.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Popular models include Ray Butts' EchoSonic (1952), the Watkins Copicat (1958), the Echoplex (1959) and the Roland Space Echo (1974).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In the Echoplex EP-2, the play head position was fixed, while a combination record and erase head was mounted on a slide, thus the delay time of the echo was adjusted by changing the distance between the record and play heads.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The Space Echo uses a free-running tape transport system to reduce tape wear, noise, and wow and flutter, and made the units more reliable and easy to transport.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] It was more reliable and sturdy than previous tape echo devices, making it easy to travel and perform with.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] It has been used by musicians in genres such as reggae, dub, trip hop, post-punk and experimental rock.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Thin magnetic tape was not entirely suited for continuous operation, however, so the tape loop has to be replaced from time to time to maintain the audio fidelity of the processed sounds.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The Binson Echorec used a rotating magnetic drum or disc (not entirely unlike those used in modern hard-disk drives) as its storage medium.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] This provided an advantage over tape, as the durable drums were able to last for many years with little deterioration in the audio quality.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In later years, tape delay effects remained popular for the way the tape compresses and distorts, "creating the impression that the echoes are receding rather than just getting quieter".
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] An alternative echo system was the so-called *oil-can delay* method, which uses electrostatic rather than electromagnetic recording.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Invented by Ray Lubow, the oil-can method uses a rotating disc of anodized aluminium coated with a suspension of carbon particles.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] An AC signal to a conductive neoprene wiper transfers the charge to the high impedance disc.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] As the particles pass by the wiper, they act as thousands of tiny capacitors, holding a small part of the charge.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] A second wiper reads this representation of the signal and sends it to a voltage amplifier that mixes it with the original source.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] To protect the charge held by the particles and to lubricate the entire assembly, the disc runs inside a sealed can with enough of a special insulating oil to assure that an even coating is applied as it spins.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The effect resembles an echo, but the whimsical nature of the storage medium causes variations in the sound that can be heard as a vibrato effect.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Some early models featured control circuitry designed to feed the output of the read wiper to the write wiper, causing a reverberant effect as well.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Many different companies marketed these devices under various names.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Fender sold the Dimension IV, the Variable Delay, the Echo-Reverb I, II, and III, and included an oil can in their Special Effects box.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Ray Lubow himself sold many different versions under the Tel-Ray/Morley brand, starting out in the early sixties with the Ad-n-echo, and eventually producing the Echo-ver-brato, the Electrostatic Delay Line, and many others into the eighties.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The bucket-brigade device (BBD) was developed at Philips in 1969.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay effects utilizing this technology eventually became available.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Notable examples include the Memory Man from Electro-Harmonix, released in 1976, and the Boss DM-2 released in 1981.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] BBD-based devices offered a convenient alternative to tape delays and leslie speakers but were eventually largely supplanted by digital delays.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Digital delay systems function by sampling the input signal using an analog-to-digital converter.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The resulting digital audio is passed through a memory buffer and recalled from the buffer a short time later.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Through feedback of some of the delayed audio back into the buffer, multiple repeats of the audio are created.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The delayed (*wet*) output may be mixed with the unmodified (*dry*) signal after, or before, it is sent to a digital-to-analog converter for output.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Digital delay effects were initially available as expensive rack-mounted units intended for use in television and audio production studios.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] One of the first was the Eventide DDL 1745 from 1971.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Another popular rack-mount digital delay was the AMS DMX 15-80 of 1978.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] As digital memory became cheaper in the 1980s, units like Lexicon PCM42, Roland SDE-3000, TC Electronic 2290 offered more than three seconds of delay time, enough to create background loops, rhythms, and phrases.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The 2290 was upgradeable to 32 seconds, and Electro-Harmonix offered a 16-second delay and looping machine.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Eventually, as costs came down further and the electronics grew smaller, they became available in the form of foot pedals.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The first digital delay offered in a pedal was the Boss DD-2 in 1984.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Rack-mounted delay units evolved into digital reverb units and on to digital multi-effects units capable of more sophisticated effects than pure delay, such as reverb and audio time stretching and pitch scaling effects.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Digital delays present an extensive array of options, including control over the time before playback of the delayed signal.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Most also allow the user to select the overall level of the processed signal in relation to the unmodified one, or the level at which the delayed signal is fed back into the memory, to be repeated again.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Some systems allow more exotic controls, such as the ability to add an audio filter and modulate the playback rate.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] While the early delay units with a long delay capacity could be used to record a riff or chord progression and then play over it, they were challenging to work with.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The Paradis Loop Delay, created in 1992, was the first unit with dedicated looping functions such as record, overdub, multiply, insert, and replace, which made it more intuitive and user-friendly.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Gibson manufactured a slightly improved version as the Echoplex Digital Pro until 2006.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] A natural development from digital delay-processing hardware was the appearance of software-based delay systems.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In large part, this coincided with the popularity of audio editing software.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Software delays, in many cases, offer much greater flexibility than even the most recent digital hardware delays.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Software implementations may offer shifting or random delay times, or the insertion of other audio effects in the feedback path.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Many software plugins have added functionality to emulate the sounds of the earlier analog units.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Abundant main memory on modern personal computers offers ample delay time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In popular and electronic music, electric guitarists use delay to produce densely overlaid textures of notes with rhythms complementary to the music.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] U2 guitarist the Edge uses delay while he plays arpeggios on electric guitar, thus creating a sustained, synth pad-like background.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Vocalists and instrumentalists use delay to add a dense or ethereal quality to their singing or playing.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Extremely long delays of 10 seconds or more are often used to create loops of a whole musical phrase.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Robert Fripp used two Revox reel-to-reel tape recorders to achieve very long delay times for solo guitar performance.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] He dubbed this technology "Frippertronics", and used it in a number of recordings.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] John Martyn was a pioneer of the Echoplex.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Perhaps the earliest indication of his use can be heard on the songs "Would You Believe Me" and "The Ocean" on the album *Stormbringer!* released in February 1970.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay effects add a time delay to an audio signal.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Blending the delayed audio with the original audio creates an echo-like effect, whereby the original audio is heard, followed by the delayed audio.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The delayed signal may be treated separately from the input audio - for example, with an equalizer.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Most delay effects allow users to set the delay time, or the amount of time between each audio playback.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] They may be synchronized to a BPM, allowing users to set time values as beat divisions.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay is used to create other effects, including reverb, chorus, and flanging.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Delay effects typically allow users to add and adjust feedback.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] By feeding some of the delayed audio back into the delay mechanism, multiple repeats of the audio are heard.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] At low feedback settings, each repeat fades in volume.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] High levels of feedback can cause the level of the output to rapidly increase, becoming louder and louder; this may be managed using a limiter.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Short delays (50 ms or less) create a sense of *broadening* the sound without creating a perceptible echo and can be used to add stereo width or simulate double-tracking (layering two performances).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] The effect is known as the precedence effect or Haas effect, after the German scientist Helmut Haas.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In a ping-pong delay, the delayed signal alternates between the two channels of a stereo program.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] In a multi-tap delay, multiple *taps* (outputs) are taken from a delay buffer, each with independent times and levels, and summed with the original signal.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Multi-tap delays can be used to create rhythmic patterns or dense, reverb-like effects.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Straight delay is also used in audio to video synchronization to align sound with visual media (e.g., on TV or web broadcasting), if the visual source is delayed.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/delay-audio-effect] Visual media can become delayed by a number of mechanisms or reasons, such as time base correction, video scaling and framebuffers, in which case the associated audio may be delayed to match the visual content.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Newton's law of gravity defines a direct relation between the mass of a central object and the speed of a smaller object in orbit around the central mass.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] to the RMS velocity Δ*V* of gas moving near the black hole in the broad emission-line region, measured from the Doppler broadening of the gaseous emission lines.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] In this formula, *R*BLR is the radius of the broad-line region; *G* is the constant of gravitation; and *f* is a poorly known "form factor" that depends on the shape of the BLR.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] While Δ*V* can be measured directly using spectroscopy, the necessary determination of *R*BLR is much less straightforward.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] This is where reverberation mapping comes into play.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] It utilizes the fact that the emission-line fluxes vary strongly in response to changes in the continuum, i.e., the light from the accretion disk near the black hole.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Put simply, if the brightness of the accretion disk varies, the emission lines, which are excited in response to the accretion disk's light, will "reverberate", that is, vary in response.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] But it will take some time for light from the accretion disk to reach the broad-line region.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Thus, the emission-line response is delayed with respect to changes in the continuum.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Assuming that this delay is solely due to light travel times, the distance traveled by the light, corresponding to the radius of the broad emission-line region, can be measured.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] At least 70active galactic nuclei have been accurately mapped in this way.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] An alternative approach is to use an empirical correlation between *R*BLR and the continuum luminosity.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Another uncertainty is the value of *f*.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] In principle, the response of the BLR to variations in the continuum could be used to map out the three-dimensional structure of the BLR.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] In practice, the amount and quality of data required to carry out such a deconvolution is prohibitive.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Until about 2004, *f* was estimated ab initio based on simple models for the structure of the BLR.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] More recently, the value of *f* has been determined so as to bring the M–sigma relation for active galaxies into the best possible agreement with the M–sigma relation for quiescent galaxies.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] When *f* is determined in this way, reverberation mapping becomes a "secondary", rather than "primary", mass estimation technique.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] Horne, Reverberation Mapping of Active Galactic Nuclei (2004).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] *Bentz, Misty C.; Katz, Sarah (January 2015).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation-mapping] *Publications of the Astronomical Society of the Pacific*.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] In acoustics, **reverberation** (commonly shortened to **reverb**) is a persistence of sound after it is produced.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] It is often created when a sound is reflected on surfaces, causing multiple reflections that build up and then decay as the sound is absorbed by the surfaces of objects in the space – which could include furniture, people, and air.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This is most noticeable when the sound source stops but the reflections continue, their amplitude decreasing, until zero is reached.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation is frequency dependent: the length of the decay, or reverberation time, receives special consideration in the architectural design of spaces which need to have specific reverberation times to achieve optimum performance for their intended activity.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] In comparison to a distinct echo, that is detectable at a minimum of 50 to 100 ms after the previous sound, reverberation is the occurrence of reflections that arrive in a sequence of less than approximately 50 ms.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] As time passes, the amplitude of the reflections gradually reduces to non-noticeable levels.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation is not limited to indoor spaces as it exists in forests and other outdoor environments where reflection exists.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation occurs naturally when a person sings, talks, or plays an instrument acoustically in a hall or performance space with sound-reflective surfaces.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation is applied artificially by using reverb effects, which simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Although reverberation can add naturalness to recorded sound by adding a sense of space, it can also reduce speech intelligibility, especially when noise is also present.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] People with hearing loss, including users of hearing aids, frequently report difficulty in understanding speech in reverberant, noisy situations.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation is also a significant source of mistakes in automatic speech recognition.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] When it comes to accurately measuring reverberation time with a meter, the term *T60* (an abbreviation for reverberation time 60 dB) is used.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] T60 provides an objective reverberation time measurement.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] It is defined as the time it takes for the sound pressure level to reduce by 60 dB, measured after the generated test signal is abruptly ended.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation time is frequently stated as a single value if measured as a wideband signal (20 Hz to 20 kHz).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] However, being frequency-dependent, it can be more precisely described in terms of frequency bands (one octave, 1/3 octave, 1/6 octave, etc.).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Being frequency dependent, the reverberation time measured in narrow bands will differ depending on the frequency band being measured.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] For precision, it is important to know what ranges of frequencies are being described by a reverberation time measurement.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] In the late 19th century, Wallace Clement Sabine started experiments at Harvard University to investigate the impact of absorption on the reverberation time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Using a portable wind chest and organ pipes as a sound source, a stopwatch and his ears, he measured the time from interruption of the source to inaudibility (a difference of roughly 60 dB).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] He found that the reverberation time is proportional to room dimensions and inversely proportional to the amount of absorption present.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The optimum reverberation time for a space in which music is played depends on the type of music that is to be played in the space.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Rooms used for speech typically need a shorter reverberation time so that speech can be understood more clearly.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] If the reflected sound from one syllable is still heard when the next syllable is spoken, it may be difficult to understand what was said.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] "Cat", "cab", and "cap" may all sound very similar.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] If on the other hand the reverberation time is too short, tonal balance and loudness may suffer.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation effects are often used in studios to add depth to sounds.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation changes the perceived spectral structure of a sound but does not alter the pitch.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Basic factors that affect a room's reverberation time include the size and shape of the enclosure as well as the materials used in the construction of the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Every object placed within the enclosure can also affect this reverberation time, including people and their belongings.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Historically, reverberation time could only be measured using a level recorder (a plotting device which graphs the noise level against time on a ribbon of moving paper).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] A loud noise is produced, and as the sound dies away the trace on the level recorder will show a distinct slope.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Analysis of this slope reveals the measured reverberation time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Some modern digital sound level meters can carry out this analysis automatically.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Several methods exist for measuring reverberation time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] An impulse can be measured by creating a sufficiently loud noise (which must have a defined cut-off point).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Impulse noise sources such as a blank pistol shot or balloon burst may be used to measure the impulse response of a room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Alternatively, a random noise signal such as pink noise or white noise may be generated through a loudspeaker, and then turned off.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This is known as the interrupted method, and the measured result is known as the interrupted response.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] A two-port measurement system can also be used to measure noise introduced into a space and compare it to what is subsequently measured in the space.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Consider sound reproduced by a loudspeaker into a room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] A recording of the sound in the room can be made and compared to what was sent to the loudspeaker.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The two signals can be compared mathematically.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This two port measurement system uses a Fourier transform to mathematically derive the impulse response of the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] From the impulse response, the reverberation time can be calculated.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Using a two-port system allows reverberation time to be measured with signals other than loud impulses.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Music or recordings of other sounds can be used.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This allows measurements to be taken in a room after the audience is present.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Reverberation time is usually stated as a decay time and is measured in seconds.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] There may or may not be any statement of the frequency band used in the measurement.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Decay time is the time it takes the signal to diminish 60 dB below the original sound.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] It is often difficult to inject enough sound into the room to measure a decay of 60 dB, particularly at lower frequencies.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] If the decay is linear, it is sufficient to measure a drop of 20 dB and multiply the time by 3, or a drop of 30 dB and multiply the time by 2.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] These are the so-called T20 and T30 measurement methods.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The RT60 reverberation time measurement is defined in the ISO 3382-1 standard for performance spaces, the ISO 3382-2 standard for ordinary rooms, and the ISO 3382-3 for open-plan offices, as well as the ASTM E2235 standard.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The concept of reverberation time implicitly supposes that the decay rate of the sound is exponential, so that the sound level diminishes regularly, at a rate of so many dB per second.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] It is not often the case in real rooms, depending on the disposition of reflective, dispersive and absorbing surfaces.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Moreover, successive measurement of the sound level often yields very different results, as differences in phase in the exciting sound build up in notably different sound waves.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Schroeder published "A new method of Measuring Reverberation Time" in the *Journal of the Acoustical Society of America*.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] He proposed to measure, not the power of the sound, but the energy, by integrating it.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This made it possible to show the variation in the rate of decay and to free acousticians from the necessity of averaging many measurements.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Sabine's reverberation equation was developed in the late 1890s in an empirical fashion.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] He established a relationship between the *T*60 of a room, its volume, and its total absorption (in sabins).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] where *c*20 is the speed of sound in the room (at 20 °C), *V* is the volume of the room in m3, *S* total surface area of room in m2, *a* is the average absorption coefficient of room surfaces, and the product *Sa* is the total absorption in sabins.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The total absorption in sabins (and hence reverberation time) generally changes depending on frequency (which is defined by the acoustic properties of the space).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The equation does not take into account room shape or losses from the sound traveling through the air (important in larger spaces).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Most rooms absorb less sound energy in the lower frequency ranges resulting in longer reverb times at lower frequencies.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Sabine concluded that the reverberation time depends upon the reflectivity of sound from various surfaces available inside the hall.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] If the reflection is coherent, the reverberation time of the hall will be longer; the sound will take more time to die out.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] where critical distance $d_{c}$ is measured in meters, volume V is measured in m³, and reverberation time *RT*60 is measured in seconds.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Eyring's reverberation time equation was proposed by Carl F.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This equation aims to better estimate the reverberation time in small rooms with relatively large quantities of sound absorption, identified by Eyring as "dead" rooms.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] These rooms tend to have lower reverberation times than larger, more acoustically live rooms.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Eyring's equation is similar in form to Sabine's equation, but includes modifications to logarithmically scale the absorption term.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The units and variables within the equation are the same as those defined for Sabine's equation.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Eyring's equation was developed from first principles using an image source model of sound reflection, as opposed to Sabine's empirical approach.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The experimental results obtained by Sabine generally agree with Eyring's equation since the two formulae become identical for very live rooms, the type in which Sabine worked.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] However, Eyring's equation becomes more valid for smaller rooms with large quantities of absorption.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] As a result, the Eyring equation is often implemented to estimate the reverberation time in recording studio control rooms or other critical listening environments with high quantities of sound absorption.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The Sabine equation tends to over-predict reverberation time for small rooms with high amounts of absorption.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] For this reason, reverberation time calculators available for smaller recording studio environments, such as home recording studios, often use Eyring's equation.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The absorption coefficient of a material is a number between 0 and 1 which indicates the proportion of sound which is absorbed by the surface compared to the proportion which is reflected back to the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] A large, fully open window would offer no reflection as any sound reaching it would pass straight out and no sound would be reflected.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] This would have an absorption coefficient of 1.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Conversely, a thick, smooth painted concrete ceiling would be the acoustic equivalent of a mirror and have an absorption coefficient very close to 0.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Absorption coefficients are frequency-dependent and are typically reported at the standard octave band centre frequencies of 125, 250, 500, 1000, 2000, and 4000 Hz.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] A single-number rating called the weighted sound absorption coefficient (*α*w) can be derived from the frequency-dependent values according to ISO 11654.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] The standard laboratory method for measuring absorption coefficients is ISO 354, which uses a reverberation room and determines the random-incidence absorption coefficient from the change in reverberation time after placing a test specimen in the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] An alternative method using an impedance tube (ISO 10534-2) measures the normal-incidence absorption coefficient for small material samples.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Values measured in a reverberation room can exceed 1.0 because edge diffraction effects increase the effective absorbing area beyond the physical dimensions of the specimen.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Gregorian chant may have developed in response to the long reverberation time of cathedrals, limiting the number of notes that could be sung before blending chaotically.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] Artificial reverberation is applied to sound using reverb effects.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/reverberation] These simulate reverb through means including echo chambers, vibrations sent through metal, and digital processing.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] For frequencies under the Schroeder frequency, certain wavelengths of sound will build up as resonances within the boundaries of the room, and the resonating frequencies can be determined using the room's dimensions.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Modes can occur in all three dimensions of a room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Axial modes are one-dimensional and build up between one set of parallel walls.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Tangential modes are two-dimensional and involve four walls bounding the space perpendicular to each other.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Finally, oblique modes concern all walls within the simplified rectilinear room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] A modal density analysis method using concepts from psychoacoustics, the "Bonello criterion", analyzes the first 48 room modes and plots the number of modes in each one-third of an octave.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] The curve increases monotonically (each one-third of an octave must have more modes than the preceding one).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Other systems to determine correct room ratios have more recently been developed.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] After determining the best dimensions of the room, using the modal density criteria, the next step is to find the correct reverberation time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] The most appropriate reverberation time depends on the use of the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] RT60 is a measure of reverberation time.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Times about 1.5 to 2 seconds are needed for opera theaters and concert halls.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] For broadcasting and recording studios and conference rooms, values under one second are frequently used.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] The recommended reverberation time is always a function of the volume of the room.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Ideally, the RT60 should have about the same value at all frequencies from 30 to 12,000 Hz.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] To get the desired RT60, several acoustics materials can be used as described in several books.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] A valuable simplification of the task was proposed by Oscar Bonello in 1979.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] It consists of using standard acoustic panels of 1 m2 hung from the walls of the room (only if the panels are parallel).
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] These panels use a combination of three Helmholtz resonators and a wooden resonant panel.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] This system gives a large acoustic absorption at low frequencies (under 500 Hz) and reduces at high frequencies to compensate for the typical absorption by people, lateral surfaces, ceilings, etc.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] In reality, there are some properties of acoustics that affect the acoustic space.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] These properties can either improve the quality of the sound or interfere with the sound.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] The application of acoustic space is very useful in architecture.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Some kinds of architecture need a proficient design to bring out the best performances.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] For example, concert halls, auditoriums, theaters, or even cathedrals.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] The task of room acoustics is to influence these parameters by designing the room in such a way that the acoustic properties of the room are maximized for its intended use.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] However, not all venues are designed with acoustics in mind.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] In this case, speaker placement will play a decisive role in the movement of sound waves, affecting clarity, loudness and overall sound quality.
[src:audio-reverb-algorithms/room-acoustics] Since the acoustic properties of rooms for different applications are almost incompatible, it is hardly possible to create a universal room that combines good speech intelligibility and good spatial music perception.
